    <subsection>
    	<title><m>X</m>-Intercept and <m>Y</m>-Intercept</title>

        <p>In a linear equation (and other types of equations), usually we are interested in its <m>x</m>-intercept and <m>y</m>-intercept because they are important in the context. For example, in <xref ref="graph-of-stapler-marker-problem">Figure</xref> about purchasing staplers and markers, the <m>x</m>-intercept implies Michael can purchase <m>40</m> stapers with no markers; the <m>y</m>-intercept implies Michael can purchase <m>100</m> markers with no staplers. Let's look at another example.</p>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Scenario</title>

            <p>A restaurant purchased <m>1,200</m> lb of flour. The restaurant uses about <m>32</m> lb of flour every day. Model the amount of flour with a linear equation, and interpret the meaning of its <m>x</m>-intercept and <m>y</m>-intercept.</p>

            <p>Since the rate of change is constant (<m>-32</m> lb every day), we can model the amount of flour at this restaurant with a linear equation:<me>y=-32x+1200</me>where <m>x</m> represents the number of days passed since <m>1,200</m> lb of flour was purchased, and <m>y</m> represents the amount of flour left (in <m>lb\text{).}</m></p>

            <p>A line's <m>x</m>-intercept is in the form of <m>(x,0)\text{.}</m> To find this line's <m>x</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>y</m> in the equation with <m>0\text{,}</m> and solve for <m>x\text{:}</m>

            <md>
                <mrow>y\amp=-32x+1200</mrow>
                <mrow>0\amp=-32x+1200</mrow>
                <mrow>0\mathbf{{}-1200}\amp=-32x+1200\mathbf{{}-1200}</mrow>
                <mrow>-1200\amp=-32x</mrow>
                <mrow>\frac{-1200}{-32}\amp=\frac{-32x}{-32}</mrow>
                <mrow>37.5\amp=x</mrow>
            </md></p>

            <p>The line's <m>x</m>-intercept is at <m>(37.5,0)\text{.}</m> It implies that <m>37.5</m> days since <m>1,200</m> lb of flour were purchased, all flour would be used up.</p>

            <p>A line's <m>y</m>-intercept is in the form of <m>(0,y)\text{.}</m> To find this line's <m>y</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>x</m> in the equation with <m>0\text{,}</m> and we have:

            <md>
                <mrow>y\amp=-32x+1200</mrow>
                <mrow>y\amp=-32(0)+1200</mrow>
                <mrow>y\amp=1200</mrow>
            </md></p>

            <p>The line's <m>y</m>-intercept is at <m>(0,1200)\text{.}</m> It implies that on the day the flour was purchased, there were <m>1,200</m> lb. Since the <m>y</m>-intercept represents the <q>starting value,</q> a better way to phrase it is simply: In the beginning, the restaurant purchased <m>1,200</m> lb of flour.</p>

        </paragraphs>

    </subsection>

