    <subsection>
        <title>Transforming between Standard Form and Slope-Intercept Form</title>

        <p>Sometimes we need to change a linear equation from standard form <m>(Ax+By=C)</m> to slope-intercept form <m>(y=mx+b)</m>, and sometimes in the other direction. We will again start the subsection with a video.</p>

        <figure><video youtube="XYNGxsFFhZw" width="70%" /></figure>

        <p>A linear equation in slope-intercept form, <m>y=mx+b</m>, tells us important information about the line: its slope <m>m</m> and <m>y</m>-intercept <m>b\text{.}</m> However, a line's standard form does not show those two important values. As a result, we often need to change a line's equation from standard form to slope-intercept form. Let's look at some examples.</p>

        <example>
        	<statement>
        		<p>Change <m>2x-3y=-6</m> to slope-intercept form, and then graph it.</p>
        	</statement>
        	<solution>
        		<p>Since a slope-intercept form looks like <m>y=mx+b\text{,}</m> we will solve for <m>y</m> in <m>2x-3y=-6\text{:}</m>
        		<md>
        			<mrow>2x-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
        			<mrow>2x-3y\mathbf{{}-2x}\amp=-6\mathbf{{}-2x}</mrow>
        			<mrow>-3y\amp=-2x-6</mrow>
        			<mrow>\frac{-3y}{-3}\amp=\frac{-2x}{-3}+\frac{-6}{-3}</mrow>
        			<mrow>y\amp=\frac{2}{3}x+2</mrow>
        		</md></p>

        		<p>In the third line, we write <m>-2x-6</m> on the right side, instead of <m>-6-2x\text{.}</m> This is because we ususally write variable terms first, and then number terms (just like in the slope-intercept form <m>y=mx+b\text{).}</m></p>

        		<p>With the line's slope and <m>y</m>-intercept found, we can graph the line by slope triangles:</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Graphing <m>2x-3y=-6 </m> with Slope Triangles</caption>
                    <image>
                    <description>This is a grid with the graph of line 2x-3y=-6. The following points are ploted: (-6,-2), (-3,0), (0,2), (3,4), (6,6).</description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[
                                xmin=-7,xmax=7,ymin=-7,ymax=7,
                                minor xtick=, minor ytick=,
                                xtick={-6,-4,...,6},ytick={-6,-4,...,6}
                            ]
                                \addplot[
                                    domain = -7:7,
                                    <->,
                                    smooth,
                                    thin,
                                    color = red,
                                ]{2/3*x+2};
						        \addplot[only marks,color=red] 
						        coordinates{
						            (-6,-2)
						            (-3,0)
						            (0,2)
						            (3,4)
						            (6,6)
						        };
						        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,2) (3,2) (3,4)};
                                \node at (axis cs: 1.5,2) [below, color=black] {$3$};
                                \node at (axis cs: 3,3) [right, color=black] {$2$};
                            \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>Compare this graphing method with the Graphing by Intercepts method in <xref ref="example-graph-by-intercepts">Example</xref>. We have more coordinates in this graph, thus we can graph the line more accurately.</p>
        	</solution>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="example-graph-standard-c-zero">
        	<statement>
        		<p>Graph <m>2x-3y=0\text{.}</m></p>
        	</statement>
        	<solution>
        		<p>We will first try to graph this line by its <m>x</m>-intercept and <m>y</m>-intercept.</p>

        		<p>The line's <m>x</m>-intercept looks like <m>(x,0)\text{,}</m> so we substitute <m>y</m> with <m>0</m> in the equation <m>2x-3y=0\text{,}</m> and we have:<md>
        			<mrow>2x-3y\amp=0</mrow>
        			<mrow>2x-3(0)\amp=0</mrow>
        			<mrow>2x\amp=0</mrow>
        			<mrow>x\amp=0</mrow>
        		</md></p>

        		<p>The line's <m>x</m>-intercept is <m>(0,0)\text{,}</m> at the origin.</p>

        		<p>The line's <m>y</m>-intercept looks like <m>(0,y)\text{,}</m> so we substitute <m>x</m> with <m>0</m> in the equation <m>2x-3y=0\text{,}</m> and we have:<md>
        			<mrow>2x-3y\amp=0</mrow>
        			<mrow>2(0)-3y\amp=0</mrow>
        			<mrow>-3y\amp=0</mrow>
        			<mrow>y\amp=0</mrow>
        		</md></p>

        		<p>The line's <m>y</m>-intercept is also <m>(0,0)\text{.}</m> Since both intercepts are the same point, there is no way to graph this line. To find another point on the line, we could substitute <m>x</m> in <m>2x-3y=0</m> with a number other than <m>0\text{,}</m> and then solve for <m>y\text{.}</m> Let's choose <m>x=1\text{:}</m><md>
        			<mrow>2x-3y\amp=0</mrow>
        			<mrow>2(1)-3y\amp=0</mrow>
        			<mrow>2-3y\amp=0</mrow>
        			<mrow>-3y\amp=-2</mrow>
        			<mrow>y\amp=\frac{2}{3}</mrow>
        		</md></p>

        		<p>The second point is <m>(1,\frac{2}{3})\text{.}</m> With <m>(0,0)</m> and <m>(1,\frac{2}{3})\text{,}</m> we can graph the line. However, it's easier to graph <m>2x-3y=0</m> if we first change it to slope-intercept mode:
        		<md>
        			<mrow>2x-3y\amp=0</mrow>
        			<mrow>2x-3y\mathbf{{}-2x}\amp=0\mathbf{{}-2x}</mrow>
        			<mrow>-3y\amp=-2x</mrow>
        			<mrow>\frac{-3y}{-3}\amp=\frac{-2x}{-3}</mrow>
        			<mrow>y\amp=\frac{2}{3}x</mrow>
        		</md></p>

        		<p>If we look at <m>y=\frac{2}{3}x</m> as <m>y=\frac{2}{3}x+0\text{,}</m> we can see the line's <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>0\text{.}</m> With the line's slope, <m>\frac{2}{3}\text{,}</m> and <m>y</m>-intercept, <m>(0,0)</m>, we can graph the line by slope triangles:</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Graphing <m>2x-3y=0 </m> with Slope Triangles</caption>
                    <image>
                    <description>This is a grid with the graph of line 2x-3y=0. The following points are ploted: (-6,-4), (-3,-2), (0,0), (3,2), (6,4).</description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[
                                xmin=-7,xmax=7,ymin=-7,ymax=7,
                                minor xtick=, minor ytick=,
                                xtick={-6,-4,-2,4,6},ytick={-6,-4,...,6}
                            ]
                                \addplot[
                                    domain = -7:7,
                                    <->,
                                    smooth,
                                    thin,
                                    color = red,
                                ]{2/3*x};
						        \addplot[only marks,color=red] 
						        coordinates{
						            (-6,-4)
						            (-3,-2)
						            (0,0)
						            (3,2)
						            (6,4)
						        };
						        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,0) (3,0) (3,2)};
                                \node at (axis cs: 1.5,0) [below, color=black] {$\Delta x=3$};
                                \node at (axis cs: 3,1) [right, color=black] {$\Delta y=2$};
                            \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>In summary, if <m>C=0</m> in a standard-form equation <m>Ax+By=C\text{,}</m> it's easier to graph it by first changing it to slope-intercept form, and then graph the line by slope triangles.</p>
        	</solution>
        </example>

        <example>
        	<statement>
        		<p>Change <m>y=\frac{2}{3}x+2</m> to standard form.</p>
        	</statement>
        	<solution>
        		<p>Once we subtract <m>\frac{2}{3}x</m> on both sides of the equation, we have<me>-\frac{2}{3}x+y=2</me>Technically, this equation is already in standard form <m>Ax+By=C\text{.}</m> However, we would like to get rid of the fraction and the leading negative sign. The full solution is:<md>
        			<mrow>y\amp=\frac{2}{3}x+2</mrow>
        			<mrow>y\mathbf{{}-\frac{2}{3}x}\amp=\frac{2}{3}x+2\mathbf{{}-\frac{2}{3}x}</mrow>
        			<mrow>-\frac{2}{3}x+y\amp=2</mrow>
        			<mrow>\mathbf{3\cdot}(-\frac{2}{3}x)+\mathbf{3\cdot}y\amp=\mathbf{3\cdot}2</mrow>
        			<mrow>-2x+3y\amp=6</mrow>
        			<mrow>\mathbf{(-1)\cdot}(-2x)+\mathbf{(-1)\cdot}3y\amp=\mathbf{(-1)\cdot}6</mrow>
        			<mrow>2x-3y\amp=-6</mrow></md></p>
        	</solution>
        </example>

    </subsection>

